    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if Hezbollah initiates a drone, missile, or air strike that impacts Israeli ground territory by March 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nFor the purposes of this market, a qualifying \"strike\" is defined as the use of aerial bombs, drones, or missiles (including cruise or ballistic missiles) launched by Hezbollah forces that physically impact land under Israeli control.\n\nIsraeli ground territory, for the purposes of this market, refers to land internationally recognized as part of the State of Israel, including all territory under de facto Israeli government administration as of October 31, 2025. This includes the Israeli-controlled Golan Heights and East Jerusalem, but excludes the West Bank and Gaza Strip.\n\nMissiles or drones that are intercepted before reaching the ground, or surface-to-air missile strikes, will not qualify for a \"Yes\" resolution—regardless of whether debris lands on Israeli soil or causes damage.\n\nThe resolution source will be a consensus of credible reporting.",
    "outcome": "Yes",
    "explanation": "\n# Executive Summary\nThe resolution to the question of whether Hezbollah would strike Israel by March 31, 2026, was definitively confirmed as \"Yes.\" The outcome was driven by a cascading series of escalations that began with the Israeli assassination of a senior Hezbollah chief in late November 2025. This prompted severe, coordinated retaliatory drone and missile strikes by Hezbollah and Iran against Israel in early December. The conflict reached its tipping point in late February and early March 2026 when diplomatic talks failed and a subsequent joint US-Israeli action against Iran triggered Hezbollah to formally open a new front, launching devastating strikes on Israeli territory.\n\n# Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2025-11-20**: Israel carried out a devastating strike that assassinated a senior Hezbollah chief, severely straining the region and marking a crucial escalation [art_general_20251120_003_9579f013].\n- **2025-12-01**: In a major escalation, Hezbollah and Iran launched a coordinated wave of cluster bomb strikes on Israel [art_politics_20251201_004_805a843f].\n- **2025-12-10**: Following further coordinated missile and drone strikes from Hezbollah and Iran, Israel conducted heavy retaliatory strikes across Lebanon [art_general_20251210_004_98403ff9].\n- **2026-03-01**: Tensions flared as Hezbollah launched fresh rocket attacks, targeting areas including Nabatieh and wounding IDF soldiers, effectively serving as a distraction for an impending Iranian missile attack following the failure of US-brokered peace talks [art_politics_20260301_005_f1a29558].\n- **2026-03-02**: Hezbollah officially announced the opening of a \"new front\" with Israel, unleashing rockets and drones into Israeli territory in retaliation for the killing of an Iranian supreme leader, finalizing the \"Yes\" resolution [art_general_20260302_004_a1ac755d].\n\n# Causal Chain Analysis\nThe root cause of the prolonged confrontation stemmed from underlying geopolitical hostilities and ongoing skirmishes between Israel and Iranian proxies in the region. The intermediate mechanism that drastically heightened the probability of a \"Yes\" resolution was Israel's targeted assassination of a senior Hezbollah chief on November 20, 2025 [art_general_20251120_003_9579f013]. This direct aggression triggered an immediate, unified response from the 'Axis of Resistance', leading to coordinated cluster bomb and drone strikes against Israel in December [art_politics_20251201_004_805a843f]. \n\nThe proximate trigger for the definitive outcome occurred in late February and early March 2026. The collapse of US-mediated diplomatic efforts eliminated any remaining diplomatic off-ramp. Concurrently, US and Israeli strikes against Iranian leadership caused Hezbollah to formally abandon its nominal ceasefire commitments, resulting in them opening a new front and launching heavy rocket attacks into northern Israel on March 1 and March 2 [art_general_20260302_004_a1ac755d].\n\n# Countervailing Factors\nInitially, diplomatic efforts led by the US, alongside pressure from European allies (such as Canada, France, and Germany urging de-escalation), pushed for a stable ceasefire along the Israel-Lebanon border. Moreover, domestic economic and political constraints in Lebanon heavily disincentivized a full-scale war. However, these forces failed because the targeted assassinations of key Hezbollah and Iranian leadership by Israel crossed established red lines, rendering diplomatic de-escalation untenable for Hezbollah's leadership.\n\n# Event Candidate Inventory\n- **E1**: Israel assassinates senior Hezbollah chief\n  - Date: 2025-11-20\n  - Why it matters causally: Broke existing rules of engagement and directly triggered Hezbollah's massive retaliatory strikes in December.\n  - Source article IDs: art_general_20251120_003_9579f013\n- **E2**: Hezbollah and Iran launch coordinated cluster bomb and drone strikes\n  - Date: 2025-12-01 to 2025-12-10\n  - Why it matters causally: Escalated the conflict beyond isolated border skirmishes, ensuring a sustained military exchange.\n  - Source article IDs: art_politics_20251201_004_805a843f, art_general_20251210_004_98403ff9\n- **E3**: US-brokered peace talks fail\n  - Date: Late February 2026\n  - Why it matters causally: Removed diplomatic obstacles preventing a full resumption of hostilities.\n  - Source article IDs: art_politics_20260301_005_f1a29558\n- **E4**: Hezbollah opens new front and launches rockets into Israel\n  - Date: 2026-03-01 to 2026-03-02\n  - Why it matters causally: Constituted the definitive, undeniable strike event fulfilling the market's resolution criteria.\n  - Source article IDs: art_politics_20260301_005_f1a29558, art_general_20260302_004_a1ac755d\n\n# Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Israel assassinates Hezbollah chief | art_general_20251120_003_9579f013 | 2025-11-20 | 0.95 | Direct catalyst for December strikes. |\n| Hezbollah and Iran launch coordinated strikes | art_politics_20251201_004_805a843f, art_general_20251210_004_98403ff9 | 2025-12-01 to 2025-12-10 | 0.95 | Major escalation phase. |\n| Diplomatic talks fail, Hezbollah resumes attacks | art_politics_20260301_005_f1a29558 | 2026-03-01 | 0.9 | Led to the final wave of strikes. |\n| Hezbollah officially opens a new front | art_general_20260302_004_a1ac755d | 2026-03-02 | 1.0 | Directly triggered the Yes resolution. |\n\n# Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThe primary uncertainty revolves around whether the December 2025 strikes alone were sufficient to trigger the resolution, or if market arbiters specifically required the unambiguous resumption of hostilities in March 2026. An alternative path could have seen the late 2025 ceasefire hold if US diplomatic efforts in early 2026 had succeeded in curbing Iranian influence over Hezbollah, which would have likely resulted in a \"No\" outcome.\n",
